{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aaac31a4-7e5e-482e-b7d1-436fdb92073d","content":"You don't need the SDK. `dotnet-trace` is a standalone .NET global tool that can be installed or downloaded directly.\n\n**Option 1 — Download the single-file build (no .NET SDK required):**\n\n```bash\n# Inside the container (linux-x64 example)\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Copy from a SDK image via multi-stage or `docker cp`:**\n\n```bash\n# From a machine with the SDK\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\ndocker cp ~/.dotnet/tools/dotnet-trace <container_id>:/tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Then collect the CPU trace:**\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n./dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (nettrace format, convertible to speedscope)\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n> **Tip:** Use `--format speedscope` to get a file you can open directly at [https://speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app) for flame-graph analysis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1c8f7292-fad3-45bc-96b8-cde85527c54d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU. This is a practical DevOps/diagnostics question.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of .NET diagnostics tools.","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"2155:214D14:5E1EC7B:66E86FB:69F00D80"},"id":"4bb39124-ca7a-43bb-8a3c-1d77bbf3e35e","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:29:45.147Z","parentId":"0b3e7c54-d0bf-4fdc-a38b-cae2a6e7846a"}
